{"title": "Evolution Creatrice", "description": "Creative Evolution (French: L'\u00c9volution cr\u00e9atrice) is a 1907 book by French philosopher Henri Bergson. Its English translation appeared in 1911. The book provides an alternate explanation for Darwin's mechanism of evolution, suggesting that evolution is motivated by an \u00e9lan vital, a \"vital impetus\" that can also be understood as humanity's natural creative impulse. The book was very popular in the early decades of the twentieth century, before the Neodarwinian synthesis was developed.<br /><br />The book also develops concepts of time (offered in Bergson's earlier work) which significantly influenced modernist writers and thinkers such as Marcel Proust. For example, Bergson's term \"duration\" refers to a more individual, subjective experience of time, as opposed to mathematical, objectively measurable \"clock time.\" In Creative Evolution, Bergson suggests that the experience of time as \"duration\" can best be understood through creative intuition, not through intellect. - Summary by Wikipedia", "duration": 40641, "language": "English", "authors": [{"id": "4730", "name": " Henri Bergson"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/evolutioncreatrice_1706_librivox/creative_evolution_1706.jpg", "copyright_year": "1911", "genres": ["*Non-fiction", "Contemporary", "Life Sciences"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "Peter Tucker"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "Peter Tucker"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "TriciaG"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "DaveC"}], "sections": [{"section": 0, "title": "Translator's note and author's introduction", "readers": [8799], "path": "http://www.archive.org/download/evolutioncreatrice_1706_librivox/evolutioncreatrice_00_bergson_64kb.mp3", "duration": 813}, {"section": 1, "title": "Chapter 1, Part 1", "readers": [8799], "path": "http://www.archive.org/download/evolutioncreatrice_1706_librivox/evolutioncreatrice_01_bergson_64kb.mp3", "duratio